Restoring the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights at the same time
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have proposed a law designed to protect organizing in unions as civil law.
"By how the unions operate, there are jobs for the middle class," says Ellison, the Democratic senator behind Minnesota, who is co-chair of the Congressional Committee.
That's why I'm so proud to present the law, together with the role model of the occasional rights of John Lewis, empowering employees.
This groundbreaking legislation will give workers the same legal options to defend themselves against discrimination in unions as in other forms of discrimination - and stop the anti-union forces
Adjusting the Labor Relations Act to allow all employees facing discrimination, if they want to join unions, sue in civil court - and assess compensation or damages - is a proper and necessary initiative.
But it's certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
The best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and other petitioners in the law are putting forward is to re-establish the American ideal.
Despite the union fighting that took place in recent years - Wisconsin, Michigan and other states - Americans once supported countries around the world to accept, expand and respect labor rights.
There were times, and millions of Americans still remember them, when the country in one breath championed democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to assembly.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his advisers supported the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that the military autocracy of Hideki Toja was replaced by democracy.
They were convinced that employees and their unions played a role in the formation of the new Japan, included the language in them and openly acknowledged that "the right of employees to gather, collectively negotiate and act is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his advisers urged the Germans to create a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
The Germans were aware that employees would need to be organized and promoted in the new nation, and therefore included a clause that openly says: “The right to create associations that will secure and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and every profession or profession.
Arrangements that will restrict this right or seek to damage it will be revoked. Measures to fulfil such a purpose are unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Human Rights Commission, which proposed the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which was adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a global treaty, the petitioners and Roosevelt included the guarantee that “everyone has the right to create and enter and enter trade unions in the protection of their interests.”
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When the country advised other countries on how to create a civil and democratic society, the Americans explained that the right to create labor unions - and their participation in collective bargaining with firms and government agencies in the position of an equal partner - must be protected.
Now that these rights are being attacked in America, it is definitely necessary to return to the American ideal that working people must have the right to organize and assert themselves in a free and open society.
As Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Today, everyone knows that the unions have not diminished the power of the nation, but have expanded it.
They have raised the standard of living of millions of people, created a market for industry, and lifted production to an unsuspected level.
Those who attack the unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History does not forget, and we should not.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human - and the extension of the protection of civil rights to prevent discrimination in the organisation of trade unions - is very late.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that have lifted America and made it a true promise of democracy.
A judge temporarily blocked a law that could have shut down all abortion clinics in Louisiana
A federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked Louisiana's law, which, according to attorneys, would likely close all five clinics conducting abortions in the state.
The regulation, enacted by the signature of Louisiana Governor Bobby Jindal in June, which is due to come into force on September 1, would require doctors performing abortions to have the right to accept a patient in a hospital within 30 miles of their practice.
The judge's order means that doctors can temporarily pursue legal abortions and, in the meantime, must obtain this permit.
"The proposing party will be able to lawfully operate and, in the meantime, obtain a permit," federal judge John deGravelles's ruling reads.
The hearing will be scheduled within a month so the judge can issue a more permanent resolution regarding the law.
Activists for abortion rights welcomed the resolution, which is the latest in a series of similar measures, and said it would give doctors more time to obtain a permit.
"Today's decision ensures that women in Louisiana are safe from a sneaky law designed to deprive them of their health and their rights," said Nancy Northup, president and executive director of the Center for Reproductive Rights, who has sought to block the law on behalf of three of the five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision also applies to doctors from two clinics that were not among the plaintiffs, and also apply for this authorisation.
Louisiana is among the eleven states that have passed similar laws, with the courts in Alabama and Mississippi declaring such measures unconstitutional.
Key parts of Texas law that would shut down most of the remaining clinics in the state were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Women's abortion rights campaigners, together with the Association of American Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, argue that the need to have this permit puts medically-necessary requirements on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion opposed the measures aiming to protect women's health, and some also welcomed the fact that clinics would be closed because of the measures.
The Center for Reproductive Rights said only one abortion doctor has a permit in Louisiana.
If all doctors in the state were forced to stop performing abortions, this doctor would also stop performing the procedure for fear of his safety, the group said.
Louisiana authorities said in response that they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while awaiting processing of a rights request.
