Prison guards in Bulgaria organize protests
Hundreds of prison service employees across Bulgaria attended a nationwide protest rally in front of the Justice Ministry in the capital Sofia.
At a peaceful demonstration, they reiterated their demand for the reintroduction of the original working conditions, which have recently changed.
Higher salaries are also on the list of demands to be discussed with interim Justice Minister Hristo Ivanov.
The supervisors symbolically protested the month against the new working hours and demanded a return to the original twenty-four-hour shifts.
Although the unions of prison guards and representatives of the Ministry of Justice met, they did not agree, the Bulgarian State Radio (BNR) reported.
"Negotiations are still ongoing," Rosen Zhelyazkov, head of the General Directorate of the Prison Service, told BNR.
Members of the Federation of Workers' Unions at the Ministry of the Interior are also expected to join the protests by prison staff staff.
Why can the universe have more dimensions and we can't see them
Physicists don't usually write bestsellers, but Brian Green of Columbia University managed to hit the black in 1999.
His book The Elegant Universe has become the most accessible way for lay people to tap into the hoot of problems that a number of theoretical physicists are dealing with today - an effort to unify two well-functioning but mutually incompatible discoveries of the 20th century: quantum theory and the theory of general relativity.
One of the reasons for the success of the Elegant Universe is undoubtedly that in the case of the search for a unified physical theory, it is not a boring story.
The physicists solved the basic problem between two key theories (for at the moment our universe is de facto divided into two worlds with different laws) and solve it so imaginatively that it is worth retelling even to the lay people.
Greene handled the complex material so fresh and engaging that he could not be blamed for how much interesting he did not include in his book.
Moreover, he mostly corrected his "error" in two other books: The Structure of the Universe and The Hidden Reality.
Apparently, even the author would not object to his book becoming obsolete, but the fact is that even after 15 years, the Elegant Universe still provides almost everything that an informed layman with the ambition to understand the world should know about this important part of theoretical physics.
It is quite likely that in the coming years it will be a little more vivid in this area (for example, due to the fact that the LHC accelerator will finally go to "full gas"), and so it is a good time to enter the Greens of the non-violently open door of the world of modern physics.
How much of the size of our universe?
The idea that our universe may have more than three spatial dimensions may sound foolish, fantastic, strange or mystical.
Nevertheless, it is concrete and completely acceptable.
To understand this, let us turn our eyes away from the universe as a whole for a moment to something more grounded, specifically to a long and thin garden hose for watering.
Imagine that you stretch the hundred-meter garden hose from one side of the canyon to the other and follow the entire scenery from a half-kilometre distance (as in the picture and on the following page).
From such a distance, you can easily record the long in a horizontal direction stretched hose, but if you do not suffer from sharpness, you can hardly recognize the thickness of the hose.
Given its great distance from the hose, you would think that an ant forced to live on a hose has only one dimension in which to walk: the left-right dimension along the hose.
When someone asks you where the ant was at the moment, you answer it with just one indication: the distance of the ant from the left (or right) end of the hose.
All we have to say is that from a half-kilometre distance, a long piece of hose looks like a one-dimensional object.
In the real world, the hose has thickness.
If we enlarge everything, we suddenly see a second dimension - in the shape of a circle wrapping the hose.
In such an enlarged view, it is clear that the ant can actually move in two independent dimensions: in the already well-known left-right dimension along the length of the hose, but also in the "dimension in/against the direction of movement of the clock hands", i.e. around the circular cross-section of the hose.
You begin to understand that to determine the position of a small ant, you need to enter two numbers: how far from the end of the hose and where there is a hose on the circle.
This reflects the fact that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional (note. Experts will notice that this chapter focuses purely on the disorder theory of strings.
The non-breakthrough aspects are discussed in Chapters 12 and 13.).
The surface of the hose is two-dimensional: one long long longitudinal dimension is represented by a straight arrow, the dimension in the direction of the circuit, marked with a circular arrow, is short and rolled.
However, there is a clear difference between the two dimensions.
The dimension along the hose is long and easily visible.
The size of the wrapping circuit of the hose is short, "rolled" and harder to notice.
To realize the existence of a circular dimension, we had to examine the hose with significantly better resolution.
This example illustrates an important feature of spatial dimensions.
That they divide into two groups.
They can be either large, large and therefore directly noticeable, or, on the contrary, small, coiled and much worse observable.
Of course, in this case, we did not exactly pretend to reveal the "rolled" dimension wrapping the thickness of the hose.
All you had to do was take the telescope to help.
But if the hose were thinner - like a hair or capillary - we would only reveal the rolled dimension with great effort.
Kaluza sent Einstein his article in 1919, in which he came up with the overwhelming idea that the spatial geometry of the universe could have more than three dimensions known to all of us.
He justified his radical claim by the fact that the additional dimension provides an elegant and compelling framework in which Einstein's general relativity and Maxwell's electromagnetic theory can be woven into a single, unified conceptual structure.
Immediately, the question arises as to how this Kaluza observation goes together with the obvious fact that we see just the three dimensions of space.
The answer, which Kaluza quietly assumed between the lines and which was clearly expressed and specified by the Swedish mathematician Oskar Klein in 1926, stands and falls, claiming that the spatial geometry of our universe can have both large and coiled dimensions.
This means that, like the dimension in the direction of the length of the hose, our universe has a large, vast and easily visible three dimensions, the existence of which we become aware of every moment.
But by analogy with the circular perimeter of the garden hose, the universe can have additional dimensions, firmly rolled into space so tiny that they have so far remained hidden even from our most perfect experimental apparatus.
To get a clearer picture of the essence of Kaluza's remarkable design, let's stay with the hose for a little while longer.
