Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed
A woman from Britain describes how she thought she would die after a misdiagnosis for many years.
After being diagnosed with another disease, Karin Rodgers spent most of her adolescence thinking she had only a few years to live.
In fact, it was Charcot-Marie-Tooth syndrome (CMT) - a group of hereditary disorders that damage nerves outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK said a misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because very little is known about the disease.
Around 23,000 people are believed to be suffering from CMT in the UK, which can show symptoms in motor skills such as muscle weakness, clumsy walking and twisted toes.
Insensitivity or pain may also occur in those affected, this condition is incurable and progressive, which means that over time the symptoms worsen.
When Rodgers was thirteen, she thought she was suffering from Freidreich ataxia (FA) - a disease that has a very poor prognosis.
She believed that before she celebrated her 18th birthday, she would be confined to a wheelchair, and dead before she was thirty.
The mother of two, who is now 51, says: "As a child, I knew I couldn't do the same things as others.
I fell down every day and everything took me longer.
I could never ride roller skates or skateboards with other children, and I was bullied at school because of the way I used to walk and run.”
When Rodgers was thirteen and she was after several operations to release her Achilles tendons and straighten her feet, she took advantage of her doctor leaving the room, and looked into her documentation, where she learned that she was suffering from the FA.
"I felt guilty because I was snooping, so I didn't tell anyone, but when I got home, I looked up information about the illness in the library and wrote to the FA Association," she says.
When they answered me, I was shocked, I was completely panicked.
I thought that by the time I'm eighteen, I'd end up in a wheelchair, and I'd be dead by the time I'm twenty-five, and in the meantime, I'm going to gradually lose all my powers.
I was all alone and planned my funeral.”
When she was seventeen, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she had anticipated, and asked her surgeon about it.
He just stood up, hugged her, and said, "Honey, I don't think you have the disease, or you'd be in a wheelchair.
I think it will be something much less life-threatening.”
After undergoing several genetic tests, it was found that he had CMT.
"When he explained to me what CMT was, I thought I was a child of fortune," she said.
