According to The Next Web, it is probably a weakness in iCloud security.
Two days ago, a tool appeared on the GitHub server that allowed you to obtain passwords for user accounts through brute force, i.e. by automatically repeating logging attempts with different passwords.
This tool has been proven to work, but Apple closed the security hole after two days.
What is certain, however, is that potential attackers had plenty of time to gain access to different accounts before publishing this tool.
For precautionary reasons, iCloud users should change their password associated with Apple ID.
The length of the password is important, not its complexity.
A length of at least 12 characters is appropriate.
To consider the leak of naked celebrity images as a reminder of the safe use of online services.
Although business servers such as Apple, Google, and Microsoft are secure much better than computers in homes or smaller businesses, uploading sensitive photos in an unprotected form is an unnecessary risk.
If you want to back up explicit photos or any other sensitive content online, encrypt the files before uploading.
It is also reasonable to set up automatic photo backup from your phone so that it only runs on wi-fi and after connecting to the charger.
Thus, you will have the opportunity to move sensitive images "to safety" in time, and most importantly, you will have the space to delete unsuccessful images, so that they will not unnecessarily take up space in the online storage.
